<HEADLINE>
MCN TAIWAN BRANCH ESTABLISHED TO PROMOTE CULTURE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA) 03/23/07  19:11:17 (By Elizabeth Hsu)
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-based Museum Computer Network (MCN), a non-profit
organization dedicated to fostering the cultural aims of museums
through the use of computer technologies, opened its Taiwan
branch Friday.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony marking the establishment of MCN in Taiwan was held at
the National Science Council, attended by MCN President Marla
Misunas, Academia Sinica Vice President Liu Tsui-jung, and
Academia Sinica  academician  Ovid  J.L.  Tzeng. Liu also chairs
the state-operated  National Digital Archives Program (NDAP)
which cooperates with the MCN in the organization of the MCN's
branch office in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
NDAP program manager Chen Shu-chun said the new institution will
work to promote digitalization of historic and cultural data of
museums in Taiwan and assist the facilities in displaying their
archives through the use of automation.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's renowned museums and academic institutions including the
National Palace Museum (NPM) , the Tainan-based National Museum
of Taiwan History under construction, and the Academia Sinica
have been working  with the NDAP to have their records  and
collection digitalized as part of efforts to commercialize their
archives, Chen said, citing a cooperative program that saw
Starbucks Coffee Company marketing products carrying images of
NPM collection.
</P>
